          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Here's the comparison, Leo:\n\n## Meshtastic vs reme — what fits in a single LoRa frame\n\n| | Meshtastic | reme (current) |\n|---|---|---|\n| LoRa frame | 256 bytes | 256 bytes (same radio) |\n| Protocol overhead | ~19 bytes header + protobuf framing | 1 byte wire type |\n| Encryption | AES-256-CTR (channel) or x25519+AES-CCM (DM) | x25519+ChaCha20-Poly1305 |\n| Crypto overhead | ~0 (CTR, no auth tag) / ~16 (CCM) | **80 bytes** (64 sig + 16 AEAD tag) |\n| Envelope overhead | Protobuf, minimal | **89 bytes** (OuterEnvelope fields) |\n| **Available for content** | **~200 chars** (app limit) / ~233 bytes raw | **~86 bytes** (~86 ASCII chars) |\n\nThe problem is clear: reme spends **169 bytes on overhead** per message vs Meshtastic's ~23. The culprits:\n\n1. **XEdDSA signature: 64 bytes** — Meshtastic only recently added this and explicitly calls it \"significant given LoRa constraints.\" Their channel messages don't sign at all; only DMs do.\n\n2. **AEAD tag: 16 bytes** — Meshtastic uses CTR mode (no authentication tag) for channel encryption. reme uses Poly1305 which adds 16 bytes. This is a security tradeoff — CTR alone is malleable.\n\n3. **OuterEnvelope fields: 89 bytes** — version (2) + routing_key (16) + timestamp (3) + ttl (3) + message_id (16) + ephemeral_key (32) + ack_hash (16) + length varint (1). The biggest items are `ephemeral_key` (32) and `routing_key` + `message_id` + `ack_hash` (48 total).\n\n## What can be done\n\n**A. Compact LoRa envelope (new wire type, biggest win: ~50-60 bytes saved)**\n\nCreate a `WireType::LoRaMessage = 0x03` with a stripped-down envelope for constrained transports:\n- Drop `version` (2 bytes) — LoRa peers negotiate version at pairing\n- Drop `routing_key` (16 bytes) — LoRa is point-to-point or small mesh, recipient is known\n- Drop `ack_hash` (16 bytes) — tombstone delivery confirmation doesn't make sense on LoRa\n- Drop `ttl_hours` (3 bytes) — LoRa messages are real-time, no store-and-forward\n- Truncate `message_id` to 8 bytes (collision-safe within a conversation)\n- Keep `ephemeral_key` (32 bytes, required for encryption)\n- Keep `inner_ciphertext`\n\nSaves ~45 bytes → overhead drops to ~124 bytes, ~132 bytes available for content.\n\n**B. Compress InnerEnvelope for FLAG_DETACHED messages (additional ~20-30 bytes)**\n\nDetached messages (already designed for constrained transports) could:\n- Truncate `from` PublicID to 8 bytes (peers already know each other's full key)\n- Drop `created_at_ms` (8→0 bytes) — use a relative counter or omit\n- Drop DAG fields entirely (already empty for detached)\n\nSaves ~30 bytes → ~162 bytes available for content.\n\n**C. Drop signature for LoRa (64 bytes saved, security tradeoff)**\n\nOn a point-to-point LoRa link where both parties share an ECDH secret, the AEAD authentication already proves the sender knows the shared secret. The XEdDSA signature provides sender attribution (distinguishing sender vs recipient) but costs 64 bytes. Making it optional for constrained transports would bring available content to **~226 bytes** — close to Meshtastic's capacity.\n\n**D. All combined: ~30 bytes overhead**\n\nWith A+B+C: ephemeral_key (32) + truncated message_id (8) + AEAD tag (16) + wire discriminator (1) + ciphertext length varint = ~58 bytes overhead. That leaves **~198 bytes for InnerEnvelope content** — essentially matching Meshtastic.\n\n## My take\n\nThe current wire format is designed for HTTP store-and-forward where bytes are cheap. For LoRa, a separate compact envelope is the right approach — and `FLAG_DETACHED` already signals \"I'm on a constrained transport.\" The signature drop (option C) is the controversial one but Meshtastic made the same call for channel messages. It could be opt-in per transport tier.\n\nThis is an architecture decision for v0.7/v0.8 (LoRa/BLE transport), not v0.5 (sneakernet). But worth documenting now so the sneakernet archive format doesn't accidentally preclude it.\n\nSources:\n- [Meshtastic Encryption Overview](https://meshtastic.org/docs/overview/encryption/)\n- [Meshtastic Encryption Limitations](https://meshtastic.org/docs/about/overview/encryption/limitations/)\n- [Meshtastic Message Architecture (DeepWiki)](https://deepwiki.com/meshtastic/protobufs/2-message-architecture)\n- [Meshtastic Forum: LoRa Packet Size](https://meshtastic.discourse.group/t/meshtastic-lora-packet-size/7953)\n- [Meshtastic Forum: Text Limit](https://meshtastic.discourse.group/t/whats-the-text-limit/11440)",
