          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>afb1********dec3</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********EMCK</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/9c6dcbb6-96b7-40c7-ac17-633166617352/tasks/afb1bccf808c2dec3.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Brainstorm: payload compression\" completed</summary>\n<result>Now I have a thorough picture of the actual protocol. Let me compute the real overhead numbers from the golden test data.\n\nFrom the golden tests:\n\n- `GOLDEN_OUTER_ENVELOPE` with 4-byte ciphertext = **93 bytes**. So fixed outer overhead = 93 - 1 (ciphertext len varint) - 4 (ciphertext) = **88 bytes** of fixed outer fields.\n- Actually let me count from the struct fields:\n  - version: 2 bytes\n  - routing_key: 16 bytes\n  - timestamp_hours (varint ~3 bytes for current epoch)\n  - ttl_hours (Some(168)): 3 bytes; None: 1 byte\n  - message_id: 16 bytes\n  - ephemeral_key: 32 bytes\n  - ack_hash: 16 bytes\n  - ciphertext length varint: 1+ bytes\n  - = 88–89 bytes fixed outer overhead (without ciphertext body)\n\n- InnerEnvelope fixed overhead for `GOLDEN_INNER_TEXT` with \"hi\" (2 chars):\n  - from: 32 bytes\n  - created_at_ms: 6 bytes varint\n  - Content variant: 1 byte\n  - body length varint: 1 byte\n  - body: 2 bytes\n  - prev_self None: 1 byte\n  - observed_heads empty: 1 byte\n  - epoch: 1 byte\n  - flags: 1 byte\n  - = 46 bytes total for \"hi\"; fixed inner overhead = 46 - 2 = **44 bytes**\n\n- Then: signature (64 bytes) appended before encryption\n- ChaCha20-Poly1305 AEAD tag: 16 bytes\n- So `inner_ciphertext` size = inner_postcard_bytes + 64 (sig) + 16 (tag) = inner_postcard + 80\n\nFor \"I'm ok, meet at Central Park entrance at 3pm\" (45 chars):\n- Inner postcard: 44 + 1 (length varint for 45) + 45 = ~90 bytes\n- + sig (64) + tag (16) = **170 bytes ciphertext**\n- + outer (88) + 1 varint + 1 wire discriminator = **260 bytes total**\n\nThe 237 byte LoRa limit is tight. Let me now give Leo a grounded analysis.\n\n---\n\nHere is a grounded analysis based on the actual codebase, with real byte counts derived from the golden wire format tests.\n\n## Actual overhead breakdown\n\nFrom `GOLDEN_OUTER_ENVELOPE` (93 bytes with 4-byte ciphertext):\n\n| Field | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| version (2x u8) | 2 |\n| routing_key | 16 |\n| timestamp_hours (varint, current epoch) | 3 |\n| ttl_hours (Some) | 3 |\n| message_id | 16 |\n| ephemeral_key | 32 |\n| ack_hash | 16 |\n| Subtotal outer fixed | **88** |\n\n`InnerEnvelope` fixed overhead (from `GOLDEN_INNER_TEXT` = 46 bytes for \"hi\"):\n\n| Field | Bytes |\n|---|---|\n| from (PublicID) | 32 |\n| created_at_ms (varint) | 6 |\n| Content variant tag | 1 |\n| body length varint | 1 |\n| prev_self None | 1 |\n| observed_heads empty | 1 |\n| epoch (0) | 1 |\n| flags | 1 |\n| Subtotal inner fixed | **44** |\n\nThen: + 64 bytes XEdDSA signature + 16 bytes Poly1305 tag = **80 bytes** crypto overhead on top of serialized inner.\n\nFor \"I'm ok, meet at Central Park entrance at 3pm\" (45 bytes UTF-8):\n- Inner serialized: 44 + 1 (varint for len 45) + 45 = **90 bytes**\n- inner_ciphertext: 90 + 64 + 16 = **170 bytes**\n- Wire total: 1 (discriminator) + 88 (outer fixed) + 1 (ciphertext len varint, 2 bytes for >127) + 170 = **261 bytes**\n\nBudget: 237 bytes. Deficit: **~24 bytes** to close.\n\n---\n\n## Approach 1: Pre-encryption compression of InnerEnvelope bytes\n\n**What would actually compress:** The InnerEnvelope postcard output for a typical short message is ~90 bytes. The dominant bytes are:\n- 32-byte `from` PublicID — high entropy, random, **incompressible**\n- 6-byte timestamp varint — low entropy but tiny\n- 64-byte body — natural language text, somewhat compressible\n- remainder — tiny fixed fields\n\nThe 32-byte PublicID alone kills general-purpose compressors. For lz4/deflate/zstd, you'd likely get **0–5 bytes** saved on the inner blob because entropy is dominated by the key bytes. Without a trained dictionary that knows to skip the key, general compression is a net loss (header overhead > savings).\n\nZstd with a **pre-shared dictionary** could theoretically suppress the key bytes, but the dictionary must be known at both ends at compress/decompress time — which is a protocol-level contract and adds a versioning dimension. Savings on 90 bytes with a good dictionary: maybe 10–15 bytes, mostly from the text portion.\n\n**Smaz** (short string compression) works only on the text body, not the whole inner blob. Applied to just the body string, smaz typically achieves 40–50% on English short sentences. For the 45-char example: ~22–27 bytes compressed vs 45. Net saving on total wire size: **~18–22 bytes**. That closes the gap, but Smaz has no Rust crate with active maintenance and is ASCII-only.\n\n**Compression oracle risk:** You note this is not TLS, and there's no cross-message secret reuse in the plaintext, so CRIM********tyle attacks don't apply. Compression before signing is fine here.\n\n**Verdict:** Pre-compression of the whole inner blob is nearly useless. Compressing only the text body with a short-string algorithm like Smaz/shoco is viable but language-dependent and fragile.\n\n---\n\n## Approach 2: Content-level text body compression\n\nThis is the most targeted intervention. The text body is the only variable-length, compressible field.\n\n**Smaz** (Salvatore Sanfilippo's original C lib, 254-symbol codebook):\n- \"I'm ok, meet at Central Park entrance at 3pm\" (45 bytes) → typically ~27–30 bytes\n- Savings: ~15–18 bytes\n\n**shoco** (statistical model, trained on English):\n- Similar ratio to Smaz on English text, slightly better on short common phrases\n- ~24–28 bytes for the example\n\n**Custom static dictionary / phrase substitution:**\n- If you control the message corpus (emergency/field comms), a 256-entry phrase table lets you encode \"I'm ok\" as 1 byte, \"meet at\" as 1 byte, etc.\n- 45-char message → plausibly 15–20 bytes with a good domain dictionary\n- Savings: **25–30 bytes** — closes the deficit entirely\n\n**6-bit ASCII packing:** The example string uses only printable ASCII (no high-bit chars). Packing 6 bits/char instead of 8:\n- 45 chars × 6 bits = 270 bits = **33.75 bytes → 34 bytes** (vs 45)\n- Saving: **11 bytes**\n- Trivially implementable, transport-indifferent, no dictionary needed\n- Limitation: no emoji/Unicode, but for LoRa use cases that's acceptable\n\n**Unicode considerations:** All of the above break for non-ASCII. If you need Unicode support, 6-bit packing is out; you'd need a different scheme or a flag indicating encoding type.\n\n**Protocol impact:** Add a new `Content::CompressedText { encoding: CompressionKind, data: Vec<u8> }` variant, or put a flag byte in the existing `TextContent`. The `flags` field in `InnerEnvelope` has bits 1–7 reserved — you could repurpose bit 1 as \"body is 6-bit-packed ASCII\" with zero struct changes.\n\n---\n\n## Approach 3: Structured content types\n\nThis is the highest-leverage approach for constrained-transport use cases. Instead of compressing text, stop sending text.\n\n**Status messages:**\n```rust\npub enum Content {\n    Text(TextContent),\n    Receipt(ReceiptContent),\n    Status(StatusMessage),   // new\n    Location(LocationMessage), // new\n    Template(TemplateMessage), // new\n}\n\npub struct StatusMessage {\n    pub code: StatusCode,  // u8 enum: ImOk, NeedHelp, AtLocation, Evacuating, ...\n    pub location: Option<CompactLocation>,\n}\n\npub struct CompactLocation {\n    pub lat: i32,   // microdegrees: lat * 1e6, fits ±90° in i32\n    pub lon: i32,   // microdegrees: lon * 1e6, fits ±180° in i32\n}\n```\n\n- `StatusCode::ImOk`: 1 byte variant + 1 byte code + 1 byte (None location) = **3 bytes**\n- \"Meet at Central Park at 3pm\":\n  - CompactLocation for Central Park: 8 bytes (2× i32)\n  - Time as minutes-since-midnight u16: 2 bytes (3pm = 900)\n  - Total: ~12–15 bytes with template framing\n\nWire saving vs the 45-char string: **30–40 bytes**, completely closing the deficit.\n\n`CompactLocation` encodes ±90°/±180° in 4 bytes each (1e6 microdegrees ≈ 0.1m precision, which is better than GPS accuracy). Alternatively, u24 at 1e5 precision (1m) = 3 bytes each for 6 bytes total.\n\n**Template messages:**\n```rust\npub struct TemplateMessage {\n    pub template_id: u8,      // 256 predefined templates\n    pub slots: Vec<SlotValue>, // compact-encoded slot values\n}\n\npub enum SlotValue {\n    Location(CompactLocation),\n    TimeMinutes(u16),\n    StatusCode(u8),\n    ShortText(u8, [u8; 16]), // length + up to 16 ASCII bytes\n}\n```\n\nThis covers \"Meet at {location} at {time}\" as template 0x07 + location (8 bytes) + time (2 bytes) = **~13 bytes** total content.\n\n**Protocol impact:** New `Content` variants. `Content` is already `#[non_exhaustive]`, so deserialization of unknown variants can return a graceful error or \"unsupported content\" display, which is the right behavior. Transport-indifferent: the ciphertext is opaque to relays; they don't inspect content.\n\n---\n\n## Approach 4: Encoding tricks on fixed fields\n\nLooking at the OuterEnvelope, there is limited room here, but:\n\n**ttl_hours removal or implicit default:** `ttl_hours: None` saves 2 bytes vs `Some(168)`. If you standardize LoRa messages as \"always use server default TTL\", you reclaim those bytes. This is a sender-side policy, not a format change.\n\n**timestamp_hours varint:** Currently 3 bytes for current epoch (~480,000 hours). At epoch 524,287 (year 2030) it stays 3 bytes (varint encodes up to 2,097,151 in 3 bytes). No savings available here.\n\n**created_at_ms precision reduction for LoRa:** The `InnerEnvelope.created_at_ms` is a u64 varint, currently 6 bytes. If you store seconds (not ms) for LoRa messages, the value is ~1,700,000,000 which encodes in 5 bytes. Saving: 1 byte. Minor.\n\n**Routing key:** 16 bytes, can't shrink without breaking relay routing.\n\n**ack_hash:** 16 bytes, required for tombstone authorization.\n\n**from PublicID:** 32 bytes, cryptographically required.\n\n**ephemeral_key:** 32 bytes, cryptographically required.\n\nThe fixed crypto fields (32 + 32 + 16 + 16 + 16 = 112 bytes) are essentially untouchable. The only tunable fixed fields save you 1–3 bytes at most.\n\n---\n\n## Summary and recommendation\n\n| Approach | Implementation effort | Savings (45-char msg) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 6-bit ASCII packing in body | Low (bit manipulation only) | ~11 bytes | ASCII only, flag in existing `flags` byte |\n| Smaz/shoco on body | Medium (add crate, new Content variant) | 15–18 bytes | English only, fragile on other languages |\n| Custom phrase dictionary | Medium | 25–30 bytes | Domain-specific, requires coordinated deploy |\n| Structured content types | Medium-High (new variants + client UI) | 30–40 bytes | The right long-term answer for this use case |\n| Pre-compressing whole inner blob | Not recommended | 0–5 bytes | High-entropy crypto key bytes kill compression |\n| Shrinking fixed outer fields | Low | 1–3 bytes | Minor, worth doing alongside anything else |\n\n**My recommendation:** Do two things:\n\n1. **Immediate/low-risk:** Implement `Content::Status(StatusMessage)` and `Content::MeetAt { location: CompactLocation, time_minutes: u16 }` variants. This covers the canonical LoRa use case (\"I'm ok, meet at X at Y\") in under 15 bytes of content, closing the deficit with room to spare. The `Content` enum is already `#[non_exhaustive]`, the groundwork is there.\n\n2. **As a fallback for freeform text on LoRa:** Implement 6-bit ASCII packing. It's a 30-line encode/decode function, zero dependencies, and reclaims 11 bytes reliably. Signal its use with `FLAG********SCII = 0x02` in the existing `flags` field — no struct changes required. For the 45-char example: 44 + 34 + 64 + 16 + 88 + 2 = 249 bytes, still 12 over budget. Combined with dropping `ttl_hours` for LoRa (save 2 bytes) and reducing timestamp precision (save 1 byte), you land at ~246 bytes — still marginal.\n\nThe honest conclusion: **free-form text of 45+ chars will not fit in 237 bytes on this protocol without structured content types**. 6-bit packing and dictionary compression get you close but not there. Structured messages are the right design for LoRa regardless of compression, because it also enables a better UX (button-based status sends rather than a keyboard on a field device).</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>50588</total_tokens><tool_uses>11</tool_uses><duration_ms>105422</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/9c6dcbb6-96b7-40c7-ac17-633166617352/tasks/afb1bccf808c2dec3.output",
