          "input": {
            "content": "# LoRa MTU Wire Format Overhead Analysis\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-25\n**Context:** Post-postcard migration (PR #141). All wire format sizes reference postcard encoding.\n**Source data:** Golden wire format tests (`crates/reme-message/tests/golden_wire_format.rs`)\n\n## Problem\n\nA typical short message like \"I'm ok, meet at Central Park entrance at 3pm\" (45 bytes) produces a ~261 byte wire payload. Meshtastic's LoRa usable payload is ~237 bytes. Even a 2-char message (\"hi\") produces ~217 bytes, leaving only ~24 bytes for content.\n\n## Current Overhead Breakdown\n\n### OuterEnvelope (from `GOLDEN_OUTER_ENVELOPE`, 93 bytes with 4-byte ciphertext)\n\n| Field | Bytes | Encoding |\n|-------|-------|----------|\n| `version` (major u8 + minor u8) | 2 | Raw |\n| `routing_key` | 16 | `[u8; 16]` raw |\n| `timestamp_hours` (u32) | 3 | Varint (~480,000 for current epoch) |\n| `ttl_hours` (Option\\<u16\\>) | 3 | Some(168): 0x01 + varint |\n| `message_id` | 16 | `[u8; 16]` raw |\n| `ephemeral_key` | 32 | `[u8; 32]` raw (X25519 public key) |\n| `ack_hash` | 16 | `[u8; 16]` raw |\n| ciphertext length varint | 1+ | Varint |\n| **Subtotal (fixed)** | **~89** | |\n\n### Crypto overhead (inside ciphertext)\n\n| Component | Bytes | Purpose |\n|-----------|-------|---------|\n| XEdDSA signature | 64 | Sender authentication, non-repudiation |\n| ChaCha20-Poly1305 AEAD tag | 16 | Integrity + authenticity |\n| **Subtotal** | **80** | |\n\n### InnerEnvelope (from `GOLDEN_INNER_TEXT`, 46 bytes for \"hi\")\n\n| Field | Bytes | Encoding |\n|-------|-------|----------|\n| `from` (PublicID) | 32 | `[u8; 32]` raw |\n| `created_at_ms` (u64) | 6 | Varint (~1.7 trillion) |\n| Content variant tag | 1 | Varint (0 = Text) |\n| String length | 1 | Varint |\n| `prev_self` (None) | 1 | 0x00 |\n| `observed_heads` (empty) | 1 | Varint length 0 |\n| `epoch` (0) | 1 | Varint |\n| `flags` | 1 | Raw u8 |\n| **Subtotal (fixed, excl. body)** | **44** | |\n\n### Wire framing\n\n| Component | Bytes |\n|-----------|-------|\n| Wire type discriminator | 1 |\n\n### Total overhead (excluding text body)\n\n```\n89 (outer) + 80 (crypto) + 44 (inner fixed) + 1 (wire type) = 214 bytes\n```\n\nAvailable for text in 237-byte LoRa frame: **~23 bytes (~23 ASCII chars)**\n\n### Example messages\n\n| Message | Body bytes | Total wire | Fits in 237B? |\n|---------|-----------|------------|---------------|\n| \"hi\" | 2 | ~217 | Yes (20B margin) |\n| \"I'm ok\" | 6 | ~221 | Yes (16B margin) |\n| \"I'm ok, meet at Central Park entrance at 3pm\" | 45 | ~261 | No (24B over) |\n| \"Need help, GPS 40.7829,-73.9654\" | 31 | ~247 | No (10B over) |\n\n## Meshtastic Comparison\n\n| | Meshtastic DM (v2.5) | reme (current) |\n|---|---|---|\n| LoRa frame | 256 bytes | 256 bytes |\n| Protocol overhead | 28 bytes (16 header + 12 PKC) | ~214 bytes |\n| Encryption | x25519 + AES-CCM (8B tag) | x25519 + ChaCha20-Poly1305 (16B tag) |\n| Signature | None (TOFU) | XEdDSA 64 bytes |\n| Ephemeral key per msg | No (static keypair) | Yes (32 bytes) |\n| Sender ID per msg | 4B in header (node ID) | 32B inside ciphertext (full PublicID) |\n| Available for content | ~200 chars | ~23 chars |\n\nMeshtastic's key savings: no per-message ephemeral key (32B), no signature (64B), 8B AEAD tag (vs 16B), 4B sender ID (vs 32B). Total: ~136 bytes less overhead.\n\n## Reduction Options\n\n### Tier 1: Field truncation (24 bytes saved, zero semantic change)\n\n| Field | Current | Proposed | Saved | Collision analysis |\n|-------|---------|----------|-------|--------------------|\n| `routing_key` | 16B | 8B | **8B** | Birthday at 1M users: P ≈ 2.7x10^-8 |\n| `message_id` | 16B | 8B | **8B** | Birthday at 10M messages: P ≈ 2.7x10^-5. Nonce-safe because each msg has fresh ephemeral key |\n| `ack_hash` | 16B | 8B | **8B** | 2^64 preimage resistance, sufficient for relay tombstone auth |\n\n**Result:** Overhead drops to ~190 bytes. Available for text: **~47 bytes**. The 45-char example fits.\n\n### Tier 2: Tier 1 + replace signature with MAC (48 more bytes saved)\n\nReplace 64-byte XEdDSA signature with 16-byte BLAKE3-keyed MAC derived from the ECDH shared secret.\n\n| Property | XEdDSA (current) | BLAKE3 MAC (proposed) |\n|----------|-------------------|-----------------------|\n| Sender auth (between parties) | Yes | Yes |\n| Non-repudiation (third-party verifiable) | Yes | No |\n| Size | 64 bytes | 16 bytes |\n| Dependency | xeddsa crate | blake3 (already in tree) |\n\nNon-repudiation is not in the current threat model (AGENTS.md). BLAKE3 is already used for KDF throughout the protocol.\n\n**Result:** Overhead drops to ~142 bytes. Available for text: **~95 bytes**. Comfortable margin.\n\n### Tier 3: Tier 2 + minor field optimizations (4 more bytes saved)\n\n| Change | Saved | Tradeoff |\n|--------|-------|----------|\n| `version` 2B → 1B (nibble-packed) | 1B | Max version 15.15 |\n| `created_at_ms` → `created_at_s` offset from 2020 epoch | 2B | Lose ms precision |\n| `ttl_hours` → `ttl_days` Option\\<u8\\> | 1B | Day-granularity TTL |\n\n**Result:** Overhead drops to ~138 bytes. Available for text: **~99 bytes**.\n\n### Summary\n\n| Tier | Overhead | Available text | Key change |\n|------|----------|---------------|------------|\n| Current | 214B | 23B | — |\n| Tier 1 (field truncation) | 190B | 47B | routing_key, message_id, ack_hash: 16→8 |\n| Tier 2 (+ MAC) | 142B | 95B | XEdDSA → BLAKE3 MAC |\n| Tier 3 (+ minor) | 138B | 99B | Timestamp, version, TTL compaction |\n\n### Rejected approaches\n\n| Approach | Why rejected |\n|----------|-------------|\n| Transport-specific envelope variants | Breaks transport indifference — a LoRa message must be valid on any transport |\n| Structured content types (Status, Location) | Can't enumerate what people want to say |\n| Pre-encryption compression | 32-byte PublicID is incompressible; kills general compressors |\n| Drop `ephemeral_key` (session mode) | Kills statelessness — the core DTN design property |\n| Truncate Poly1305 tag | 8 bytes saved not worth the security regression |\n| Shorter signature scheme (BLS) | 48 bytes, slower, no X25519 integration |\n\n### Not rejected but deferred (requires design work)\n\n| Approach | Saved | Complexity |\n|----------|-------|------------|\n| `from` 32B → 8B sender hint | 24B | Needs contact-lookup state, first-msg exception |\n| 6-bit ASCII body packing | ~25% of body | ASCII only, flag in existing `flags` byte |\n| Symmetric ratchet (amortize DH) | 32B (ephemeral_key) | Needs session establishment protocol |\n\n## Protocol Comparison (crypto/envelope overhead)\n\n| Protocol | Overhead | Sender auth | Forward secrecy | Note |\n|----------|----------|-------------|-----------------|------|\n| reme (current) | ~214B | XEdDSA sig | None | Stateless, DTN-first |\n| reme Tier 1 | ~190B | XEdDSA sig | None | Field truncation only |\n| reme Tier 2 | ~142B | BLAKE3 MAC | None | Drop non-repudiation |\n| Meshtastic DM | ~28B | TOFU only | None | Static keypairs, no sig |\n| Signal (steady state) | ~24-56B | Deniable (KDF) | Per-message | Requires session state |\n| Noise_NK | 48B | Anonymous | None | Bare crypto, no metadata |\n| Noise_X | 96B | Authenticated | Session-level | Sender static in ciphertext |\n| COSE_Encrypt0 (PSK) | ~28-42B | None | None | Bare AEAD wrapper |\n| LoRaWAN MAC | 13B | Pre-provisioned | None | Infrastructure-dependent |\n| BPSec BCB (DTN) | ~43-53B | Symmetric BIB | None | CBOR overhead, store-and-forward |\n\nKey insight from Noise: the **crypto floor is 48 bytes** (32 ephemeral + 16 AEAD tag). reme is at that floor. The excess is entirely metadata (routing, dedup, tombstone auth, timestamps).\n\n## Recommendation\n\n**Tier 1 (field truncation) should be implemented before v0.5.** It's the highest-leverage change with zero semantic impact — just narrowing three array sizes. Gets the 45-char example message to fit in a single LoRa frame.\n\n**Tier 2 (MAC) is a crypto model change** — worth designing but should be a deliberate decision with threat model review, not a size optimization hack.\n\n## Interaction with chunking\n\nChunking remains necessary for longer messages regardless of these optimizations. The overhead analysis here determines the **chunk payload budget** — how many useful bytes fit per chunk. With Tier 1, each chunk carries ~47 bytes of content. With Tier 2, ~95 bytes. This directly affects the number of LoRa frames needed per message and therefore delivery latency and reliability.\n",
