is not widget-composition-heavy — it is a relatively linear chat UI with popups, where most complexity is in state management and async I/O wiring, not widget composition.\n\n**Dependency trust.** 47 stars, effectively archived. Maintainer's README says \"there are much better alternatives.\" This is a clear signal: do not adopt.\n\n**Migration cost vs. benefit.** Negative. The project is abandoned.\n\n**Verdict: Rejected.** Archived by the maintainer.\n\n---\n\n### 5. ratatui-interact\n\n**What it is.** Focus management (`FocusManager<T>` with Tab/Shift+Tab navigation) and a set of interactive widgets (CheckBox, Input, Button, Select, PopupDialog, MenuBar, etc.) with mouse support and click region hit-testing. Addresses exactly the gap ratatui leaves around focus and mouse.\n\n**Complexity reduction.** `FocusManager` would replace reme's manual `Focus` enum + popup-priority dispatch chain in `handle_key_event`. The `PopupDialog` widget could replace the hand-rolled popup structs. This is the most targeted solution to reme's actual pain points without requiring an architectural overhaul. You keep the Tokio event loop, keep the `App` struct, keep the `Action` enum — you just swap the focus/popup boilerplate.\n\nFor v0.5's export/import popups specifically, `PopupDialog` with `FocusManager` entries would add each new popup with no new `show_*` bool and no new dispatch branch — just registering a new element in the focus manager.\n\n**Dependency trust.** 21 stars, no GitHub releases, solo project (Brainwires), no community. For a security-focused messaging app, this is a higher trust risk than rat-salsa. It sits directly in the input handling path. Low audit surface, unproven in production.\n\n**Migration cost vs. benefit.** Targeted and low-migration if you adopt only `FocusManager` + `PopupDialog`. The widget set (Input, Button, etc.) would require replacing tui-textarea and other existing widgets — avoid that.\n\n**Stars/activity.** 21 stars, 46 commits, no releases