ttern of encrypting the announce payload to the bootstrap server's public key (preventing passive enumeration of users) is worth adopting.\n\n3. **Time-based peer expiry with configurable TTL:** reme's `refresh_interval_secs` (default 300) for peer re-verification is more aggressive than Photon's 7-day expiry. Both are valid for their contexts (reme's ephemeral LAN peers vs Photon's WAN peer directory).\n\n### 6. Status/Ping-Pong Protocol\n\n**Photon** (`src/network/fgtw/protocol.rs` lines 37-76, `src/network/status.rs`):\n- `StatusPing`: Contains Eagle Time timestamp, sender pubkey, BLAKE3 provenance hash (`BLAKE3(sender_pubkey || timestamp_nanos)`), and Ed25519 signature over the provenance hash.\n- `StatusPong`: Echoes the same provenance hash (proves it was received), plus per-conversation `SyncRecord` entries with `last_received_osc` for efficient resync.\n- The sync records in pong are notable: they tell the peer \"for conversation X, the last message I received was at time Y\", enabling the peer to retransmit only what was missed.\n- Replay protection via provenance hash (timestamp + pubkey).\n- Hysteresis for offline detection: `failed_pings` counter (line 649 in `status.rs`) prevents flapping on single lost packets.\n\n**reme's peer verification** (from `CLAUDE.md` architecture description):\n- HTTP challenge-response: discovered mDNS peers are verified by sending a challenge to their embedded HTTP server.\n- Two consecutive verification failures trigger removal (ephemeral circuit breaker).\n- No sync record exchange -- message synchronization happens through DAG heads and tombstones.\n\n**Assessment and recommendations:**\n\n1. **Sync records in pong:** This is a genuinely useful pattern. Photon's pong includes \"here's where I am in each conversation\" which enables efficient retransmission. reme achieves similar functionality through DAG `observed_heads`, but those are per-message overhead. A lightweight sync exchange during peer verification could reduc