          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Now I have the full picture. Here's the answer:\n\n## Briar's framing — there is no Bluetooth-specific chunking\n\nBriar doesn't chunk at the Bluetooth layer at all. The BTP framing is **transport-agnostic** — the same frame structure runs over Bluetooth RFCOMM, TCP, Tor, and removable drives. Bluetooth RFCOMM provides a reliable byte stream (like TCP), so Briar just writes BTP frames to it.\n\n### The frame structure\n\nFrom `TransportConstants.java` and the BTP spec:\n\n```\nStream = Tag (16B) + StreamHeader (82B) + Frame₀ + Frame₁ + ... + Frameₙ (final)\n\nFrame layout:\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ Encrypted header (20B)  │  Encrypted payload+pad + MAC   │\n│  4B plaintext + 16B MAC │  ≤988B payload + pad + 16B MAC │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nMAX_FRAME_LENGTH = 1024 bytes total\n```\n\nBreaking down the overhead:\n\n| Component | Size | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| Frame header plaintext | 4B | `payloadLength` (2B) + `paddingLength` (2B), high bit of first byte = `finalFrame` flag |\n| Frame header MAC | 16B | XSalsa20/Poly1305 auth tag over header |\n| Payload | 0–988B | Actual data |\n| Padding | 0–988B | Zero-filled, payload+padding ≤ 988B |\n| Payload MAC | 16B | XSalsa20/Poly1305 auth tag over payload+padding |\n| **Total** | **≤1024B** | |\n\nSo per frame: **36 bytes overhead** (4B header + 16B header MAC + 16B payload MAC), **988 bytes max payload**. That's **3.5% overhead** at max payload, which is very efficient.\n\n### Why 1024-byte frames?\n\nThis is the key design decision. From `FrameEncoder.java` — the nonce is deterministic (derived from `frameNumber` + header/body flag bit), never transmitted. The frame size is fixed at 1024 bytes max regardless of transport.\n\n1024B is a sweet spot because:\n- Fits comfortably within Bluetooth RFCOMM's MTU (which is negotiated, typically 672B–32KB depending on the link)\n- Small enough for quick flush on lossy links — if you lose a frame, you lose ≤1KB\n- Large enough that the 36B overhead is negligible\n- Padding to uniform size prevents traffic analysis (all frames look the same length on the wire)\n\n### How the writer works\n\n`StreamWriterImpl` is a standard buffered `OutputStream`:\n- Accumulates bytes into a 988-byte buffer\n- When full → emits a frame automatically\n- On `flush()` → emits a partial frame (payload < 988, with padding to obscure actual length)\n- On `close()`/`sendEndOfStream()` → emits a final frame (high bit set in header)\n\nThe encrypter (`StreamEncrypterImpl`) does two separate AEAD operations per frame:\n1. Encrypt + MAC the 4-byte header (nonce derived from `frameNumber | 0x80`)\n2. Encrypt + MAC the payload+padding (nonce derived from `frameNumber`)\n\nHeader and body use **different nonces from the same frame number** (distinguished by the high bit). This means the header can be decrypted independently to learn the payload/padding lengths before reading the rest of the frame — important for the reader to know how many more bytes to read.\n\n### The practical answer to your question\n\nBriar doesn't balance MTU and overhead at the Bluetooth layer because **RFCOMM already handles it**. RFCOMM is a stream protocol (like TCP) that fragments internally to fit the Bluetooth baseband's packet sizes. Briar just writes 1024-byte BTP frames to the RFCOMM stream and lets the Bluetooth stack handle L2CAP segmentation.\n\nIf reme adds BLE (not classic BT RFCOMM), the situation is different — BLE GATT has a 20–512 byte MTU per characteristic write, no automatic fragmentation, and no reliable stream abstraction. You'd need an actual chunking layer on top. Briar sidesteps this entirely by using classic Bluetooth, which is why they have no BLE support despite years of development.",
