          "text": "Now I can do the real comparison. Here's the breakdown:\n\n## The real overhead comparison\n\nBriar's 36B is **per-frame inside a session**. But a full Briar message transfer actually costs:\n\n```\nPer-connection (paid once, amortized across all messages in session):\n  Tag:              16B   (stream recognition)\n  Stream header:    82B   (nonce 24B + encrypted version/streamNumber/frameKey 42B + MAC 16B)\n  BHP handshake:    ~200B (ephemeral keys + proofs, paid once per session)\n  ─────────────────────\n  Session setup:    ~298B\n\nPer-frame (transport layer):\n  Header + MAC:     20B   (4B header + 16B MAC)\n  Payload MAC:      16B\n  ─────────────────────\n  Per-frame:        36B   (over 988B payload = 3.5%)\n\nPer-message (BSP layer, inside the frame payload):\n  Record type:      1B\n  Group ID:         32B\n  Timestamp:        8B\n  Message body:     variable (BDF-encoded)\n  ─────────────────────\n  BSP overhead:     ~41B+\n```\n\nreme's overhead is **per-message, stateless** — no session to amortize over:\n\n```\nOuterEnvelope (plaintext metadata):\n  version:          2B    (major + minor)\n  routing_key:      16B\n  timestamp_hours:  4B\n  ttl_hours:        ~3B   (Option<u16> via postcard)\n  message_id:       16B\n  ephemeral_key:    32B   (THIS is what Briar pays once per session)\n  ack_hash:         16B\n  ─────────────────────\n  Outer overhead:   ~89B\n\nInnerEnvelope (encrypted):\n  from (PublicID):  32B\n  created_at_ms:    8B\n  prev_self:        ~9B   (Option<ContentId>)\n  observed_heads:   ~9B+  (Vec<ContentId>)\n  epoch:            2B\n  flags:            1B\n  ─────────────────────\n  Inner overhead:   ~61B\n\nCrypto:\n  AEAD nonce:       12B   (or derived, depending on impl)\n  AEAD tag:         16B\n  XEdDSA signature: 64B   (appended before encryption)\n  ─────────────────────\n  Crypto overhead:  ~92B\n\nTotal per-message: ~242B overhead + content\n```\n\nSo: **242B (reme) vs ~77B (Briar per-message, assuming amortized session)**. But:\n\n### Why reme's overhead is 3x larger — and why that's correct\n\nThe 165B difference comes from three things:\n\n| What | reme pays | Briar pays | Difference |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Ephemeral key** | 32B per message | 0 (session key) | +32B |\n| **XEdDSA signature** | 64B per message | 0 (session auth) | +64B |\n| **Sender identity** | 32B per message (PublicID in inner) | 0 (known from session) | +32B |\n| **Ack hash** | 16B per message | 0 (not applicable) | +16B |\n| **DAG fields** | ~21B per message | ~41B (BSP group+timestamp) | -20B |\n\nThe first three items (128B) are the price of **stateless encryption**. Briar pays them once per session because it maintains session state. reme pays them every message because any message must be independently decryptable without session context. That's the DTN trade-off — you can't amortize over a session if there is no session.\n\nThe signature (64B) is particularly notable — Briar authenticates via session-level proof-of-ownership (BHP), so individual messages don't carry signatures. reme signs every message individually because the message might arrive via a different transport than the sender used, weeks later, with no session context.\n\n**This is not waste — it's the cost of reme's design goals.** For a \"hello\" message (~10 bytes of content), reme's overhead is ~96% of the envelope. For a typical text message (~200 bytes), it's ~55%. For constrained transports (LoRa), `FLAG_DETACHED` saves ~21B by dropping DAG fields, bringing it to ~221B overhead — still significant on a 256B LoRa packet.\n\nIf the overhead ever becomes a real problem on constrained transports, the options are:\n1. Session-based encryption for peers with stable connectivity (opt-in, per-conversation)\n2. Compressed ephemeral keys (X25519 is already 32B, can't shrink)\n3. Drop the signature on Tier 3/detached messages (authenticate via ECDH binding only — weaker but saves 64B)",
