imate contact-matched peer cannot be verified and registered because `peer_index` would also hit the same cap. The fix is to separate the caps (e.g., a dedicated `max_strangers` config field, or cap strangers at `max_peers / 2`, or at a fixed constant independent of `max_peers`).\n\n### 2. `drain_matching_strangers` re-decodes TXT records — O(n) decoding per contact addition (Confidence: 80)\n\n**File:** `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`, lines 598–612.\n\n`drain_matching_strangers` iterates the entire `stranger_cache`, calling `decode_txt` on every entry to re-extract the routing key. The routing key was already decoded once in `handle_discovered` (line 296) and was the sole reason for caching the peer. Decoding it again means: (a) a second allocation + parse per cached entry, and (b) if `decode_txt` fails on an already-cached entry (which shouldn't happen, but it silently discards that entry rather than logging). The cleaner fix is to store the routing key alongside the peer in the cache. Change `stranger_cache` from `HashMap<String, RawDiscoveredPeer>` to `HashMap<String, (RawDiscoveredPeer, [u8; 16])>` and populate the routing key at insertion time. `drain_matching_strangers` then becomes a simple key comparison with no parsing, and the silent-discard on `decode_txt` failure disappears.\n\n```rust\n// current (fragile, O(n*parse))\nstranger_cache: HashMap<String, RawDiscoveredPeer>\n\n// better\nstranger_cache: HashMap<String, (RawDiscoveredPeer, [u8; 16])>\n```\n\n### 3. Stale stranger can re-enter cache after being re-processed and failing verification (Confidence: 82)\n\n**File:** `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`, lines 166–174.\n\nIn the `contact_rx` arm, `drain_matching_strangers` removes and returns matching cached strangers, then calls `handle_discovered` on each. If verification fails (no address passes, network down, etc.), `handle_discovered` returns early at line 399 — it neither adds the peer to `peer_index` nor puts it back in `stra