          "text": "## Design\n\n### Problem\n\n`refresh_all_peers` verifies each peer sequentially. With a 5s HTTP timeout and `max_peers = 256`, a full refresh of unreachable peers blocks the controller's `select!` loop for up to ~21 minutes, preventing mDNS event processing and contact updates.\n\n### Solution\n\nReplace the sequential `for` loop with `JoinSet`. Each verification is spawned as an independent task owning cloned data (`name`, `url`, `identity`, `http_client`). Results are collected via `join_next()` and applied to `peer_index` as before.\n\n### Key design decisions\n\n**Ownership:** `verify_peer_identity` currently takes `&self`. We can't use it from spawned tasks (borrow issues). Extract the HTTP verification into a standalone `async fn` that takes owned parameters — `reqwest::Client`, `url: String`, `candidates: Vec<PublicID>`. This function is purely I/O with no `self` dependency.\n\n**No concurrency limit:** `max_peers` defaults to 256. All peers verify concurrently via the shared `reqwest::Client` connection pool. No semaphore needed.\n\n**Result processing:** After all tasks complete, iterate results and apply the same success/failure logic to `peer_index`. This keeps mutation sequential and simple.\n\n### Scope\n\n- **Changed file:** `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs` only\n- Extract `verify_peer_identity_standalone` (or similar) as a free async fn\n- Rewrite `refresh_all_peers` to use `JoinSet`\n- Existing `verify_peer_identity(&self, ...)` stays for use in `handle_discovered`\n- No new dependencies (JoinSet is in tokio)\n\n### Testing\n\n- Existing tests continue to pass (refresh behavior is unchanged functionally)\n- No new unit tests needed — the logic is identical, only the execution strategy changes. The existing `failure_count` and `handle_lost` tests cover the mutation side.\n\nDoes this design look right?",
