            "content": "# Parallelize periodic peer refresh\n\n**Issue:** #101\n**Date:** 2026-03-27\n**Status:** Design approved\n\n## Problem\n\n`refresh_all_peers()` re-verifies tracked peers sequentially. With a 5-second HTTP timeout per peer and `max_peers = 256`, a full refresh of unreachable peers can take over 20 minutes. During that time, the controller's `select!` loop is blocked — no mDNS events or contact updates are processed.\n\n## Design: JoinSet-based concurrent verification\n\n### Approach\n\nReplace the sequential `for` loop in `refresh_all_peers` with `tokio::task::JoinSet`. Each verification is spawned as an independent task owning cloned data. Results are collected via `join_next()` and applied to `peer_index` sequentially (same mutation logic as today).\n\n### Extracted function\n\n`verify_peer_identity` currently takes `&self` (borrows the HTTP client). Spawned tasks can't borrow `self`. Extract the HTTP verification logic into a standalone async function:\n\n```rust\nasync fn verify_identity(\n    http_client: reqwest::Client,\n    base_url: String,\n    candidates: Vec<PublicID>,\n) -> Result<Option<PublicID>, reqwest::Error>\n```\n\nThis function performs the same challenge-response protocol as `verify_peer_identity` but owns all its data. The existing `verify_peer_identity(&self, ...)` method becomes a thin wrapper that calls the standalone function with `self.http_client.clone()`.\n\n### JoinSet usage\n\n```rust\nasync fn refresh_all_peers(&mut self, coordinator: &TransportCoordinator) {\n    let peers: Vec<(String, String, PublicID)> = /* clone from peer_index */;\n\n    let mut set = JoinSet::new();\n    for (name, url, identity) in peers {\n        let client = self.http_client.clone(); // cheap: shares connection pool\n        set.spawn(async move {\n            let candidates = vec![identity];\n            let result = verify_identity(client, url, candidates).await;\n            (name, result)\n        });\n    }\n\n    while let Some(res) = set.join_next().await {\n        match res {\n            Ok((name, result)) => { /* apply success/failure logic to peer_index */ }\n            Err(e) => warn!(\"Refresh task panicked: {e}\"),\n        }\n    }\n    // remove stale peers after all results collected\n}\n```\n\n### Concurrency\n\nNo explicit limit. `max_peers` (default 256) bounds the number of spawned tasks. All verifications share the `reqwest::Client` connection pool. 256 concurrent HTTP requests with 5s timeout is modest.\n\n### Scope\n\n- **Changed file:** `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs` only\n- Extract `verify_identity` standalone async fn\n- `verify_peer_identity(&self, ...)` becomes a wrapper calling the standalone fn\n- Rewrite `refresh_all_peers` to use `JoinSet`\n- No new dependencies (`JoinSet` is in `tokio::task`)\n- No config changes\n\n### What this does NOT change\n\n- Identity verification protocol (same challenge-response)\n- Failure counting and circuit breaker logic (same thresholds)\n- Peer removal behavior\n- `handle_discovered` flow (still uses `verify_peer_identity(&self, ...)`)\n\n### Testing\n\nExisting tests cover the mutation logic (`failure_count`, `handle_lost`, `remove_peer`). The verification extraction is a pure refactor — same logic, different ownership. No new tests needed beyond verifying existing ones pass.\n",
